│ 1.6. The Eulerian step                                                       │
│                                                                              │
│ The Eulerian step accounts for the transport of the mate- rial due to its    │
│ motion relative to the mesh. In practice, the                                │
│                                                                              │
│ Eulerian step usually amounts to a projection of the solution from one mesh  │
│ on to another rather than the solution of con- vective partial differential  │
│ equation,                                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ $$                                                                           │
│ \frac {\partial \phi}{\partial t} + \sum_ {i} w _ {i} \frac {\partial        │
│ \phi}{\partial x _ {i}} = 0.                                                 │
│ $$                                                                           │
│ ![Formula](https://cdn.dev.atominnolab.com/wisdoc/formulas/20260521-468f2e2f │
│ -3979-4109-b1de-777cd9df8be2/page_043_block_003.png)                         │
│                                                                              │
│                                                                              │
│ *(1.106)*                                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ In the following discussion, the transport algorithms are developed from a   │
│ largely geometrical viewpoint in keeping with the idea that the solution is  │
│ being projected from one mesh to another. There are other approaches to      │
│ developing transport algorithms that lead to ones that are different from    │
│ those presented here, and the interested reader is referred to [BEN 92a].    │
│                                                                              │
│ The two most desirable qualities in a transport algorithm are conservation   │
│ and monotonicity. Conservation requires that the integral of the transport   │
│ variable over the domain remain unchanged by the transport. Applying this    │
│ require- ment to the density, for example, is equivalent to requiring the    │
│ conservation of mass. Not all the solution variables, how- ever, are         │
│ governed by physical conservation laws, e.g. stress is not conserved, but    │
│ they are transported as if they are. The requirement of monotonicity is that │
│ the transport should not introduce any new maxima or minima in the solution  │
│ or amplify the existing ones. This means that no numerical os- cillations    │
│ will be introduced into the solution by the trans- port algorithm, which was │
│ a serious problem with the ﬁrst method.                                      │
│                                                                              │
│ From a practical standpoint, a minimum of second-order accuracy is a third   │
│ requirement. First-order accuracy exces- sively diffuses the solution unless │
│ a very ﬁne mesh is used in the calculation. Since the Lagrangian step is     │
│ generally no bet- ter than the second-order accurate, third-                 │
│                                                                              │
